##Will the world economy be brought down by the global escalation of the epidemic?

Lifeweek

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

By Xie Jiu

While the outbreak in China is easing, the outbreak outside China is suddenly escalating. Since February 25, the number of newly confirmed cases outside China has exceeded that in China, and the NCP epidemic has entered the 2.0 phase of globalization.

At present, the number of newly diagnosed cases in South Korea has surpassed that of China. Japan, Iran, Italy and other countries have all begun to be hit hard. The epidemic has spread to more than 40 countries on five continents. World Health Organization Director General Tan Desai announced on the 28th, the new pneumonia epidemic will be raised from the "high" to the "very high" global risk level, a number of countries have also warned that the new pneumonia epidemic may be a global pandemic.

As the outbreak escalated around the world, the most sensitive US stock markets began to plummet, falling more than 12 per cent in the past week and plunging on the back of US stocks. The global panic that followed the outbreak has only recently begun.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After more than a month of outbreaks in China, global stock markets, led by the United States, were largely unimpressed. Even China's a-share market, which had only a short-term slump, quickly rebounded strongly. The main reason for the muted performance of global capital markets is the widely held belief that China's new pneumonia outbreak, while having an impact on the global economy, is local and short-term. In one of the clearest examples, apple's shares rose slightly on Feb. 17 after the company issued an earnings warning that quarterly revenue targets would not be met because of the outbreak. For investors believe the short-term effects will soon fade as China's epidemic is brought under control.

But as the epidemic began to spread around the world, investors began to realize that the impact of the new pneumonia epidemic was much greater than expected and that the economic impact would no longer be local and short-term, it could escalate into a full-blown, long-term shock that would be too much for an already fragile global economy to absorb. The panic finally broke out and global capital markets tumbled. Again, in the case of Apple, investors paid little attention when the company issued its earnings warning on Feb. 17, and the company's share price has fallen sharply since Feb. 24 as the epidemic spread around the world, it was also the start of a massive sell-off in the US stock market.

Image | visual China

After the subprime crisis, the US stock market began in 2009, ushered in a 10-year bull market, in the past 10 years, although also experienced a lot of global panic events, but never as recently as, in a few days continued to plunge, this was only in the darkest moments of the subprime crisis in 2008, when many began to believe that America's decade-long bull market might end in a new bout of pneumonia. As the U.S. stock market tumbled and investors began buying safe haven U.S. Treasury securities, the yield on the 10 year U.S. Treasury note fell sharply, falling below the 1.4 percent threshold that economists in the United States define as, that would send a strong signal that the economy is heading for a recession.

The main reason for the panic in us-led global stock markets is that investors fear the global economy could be dragged down if the new pneumonia epidemic continues on its course. Because in 2019, the global economy was already exhausted, with most major economies growing at the slowest pace in recent years, and many economists even compared the current economy to the Great Depression of the 1930s. Against this backdrop, if new coronary pneumonia spreads globally, the world economy, already on the brink of recession, will no doubt suffer further, possibly entering a real deep recession.

Given the current global economic downturn, it is easy to see why global capital markets are in such a funk. In the case of several advanced economies, U.S. GDP grew by 2.3 percent in 2019, well below the 3 percent target and the lowest in three years, as Donald Trump's fiscal stimulus and tax reform bonuses ebbed, the economy has lost momentum again, with many economic indicators signaling a recession since the second half of last year, leading the Federal Reserve to cut interest rates three times in the past year.

Europe has been stuck in a quagmire. Since the European debt crisis, the European economy has been on the verge of recession. With the deterioration of the international trade environment in recent years, the growth rate of the leading German economy has dropped significantly, it grew by just 0.6% in 2019. Japan's economy has been stuck in a Rut, growing by just 0.7% last year and falling into negative territory in the fourth quarter of last year. Japan had hoped that the Tokyo Olympics would boost its economy, but as the outbreak escalated, it faced the risk that the games would be canceled, another blow to the Japanese economy.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In Japanese supermarkets, some paper products are sold out

Emerging economies have been a major contributor to global growth in recent years, but growth has also slowed markedly. China's economy grew 6.1 percent last year, the slowest pace in more than two decades. India has been the world's fastest growing economy in recent years, but the myth of India has been shattered since last year, when it plummeted from nearly 8% to 5% , its lowest level in more than a decade.

In the face of their own difficulties, major economies are looking for new ways and means to stimulate their economies, but there are no effective ways to do so other than easing fiscal and monetary policies. In 2019, dozens of countries around the world have collectively cut interest rates to stimulate their economies, it is not hard to see the extent of the current weakness in the global economy.

The fragile global economy will not be able to withstand such a blow if the NCP epidemic can not be brought under control in time for it to eventually spread around the world. To contain the epidemic, countries around the world will inevitably contract economic activity, and even if less controlled than China's, the pace of economic expansion will suffer. To protect its citizens, countries will tighten immigration controls, much of their economic activity will be shut down, and tourism, education, investment and so on will all shrink. In the current era of globalization, no country can exist apart from others, and when the dynamism of the global economy begins to shrink from within to without, economic growth will spiral downward if the epidemic lasts too long, the great global recession is no alarmist tale.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the midst of a great recession, populist forces tend to rise, and in the most extreme cases in human history, countries such as pre-world War II Germany have even gone to war to find a way out. And it turns out that a lot of wartime demand, for example, in the United States, after the Great Depression of the 1930s, it wasn't the New Deal that really saved the American economy, it was the Second World War, the US economy doubled in just a few years, establishing itself as the world's dominant power.

At the moment, the economic crisis is unlikely to trigger a global war, but another form of war is not. It is a trade war. Will the trade war, which has just abated, start to pick up again under the economic pressure of the epidemic? Is certainly something to be wary of at the moment.

History has shown that starting a trade war does not help the domestic economy, but rather accelerates the global crisis. An important trigger for the Great Depression of the 1930s was America's tariff act of 1930, which imposed steep tariffs on foreign goods, averaging nearly 20% . The US tariff law provoked retaliation, a global trade war that collapsed, eventually hastening the US and global recession and triggering the most famous global depression in history.

The current global outbreak of new coronavirus is also a test of human wisdom. Only global cooperation, not beggar-thy-neighbour cooperation, is the real way out of this crisis.
